---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import { LATEST_TAG } from '../../site-version';
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Session Topology"
  description="How ostk's anchor + lineage + drain snapshots + sub-stacks compose to give you crash recovery, work isolation, transient-client lifecycle, and mid-flight hot-rehydrate."
  sectionLabel="SECTION_03 // SESSION_MGMT"
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    Sessions outlive everything that drives them — clients disconnect, daemons crash, workers hang. Four problems, four compositions, one shape: the daemon is a cache, not a ledger; the journal is the truth.
  </p>

  <!-- Problem 01 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_01 // DAEMON_CRASHED_DURING_WORK</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">My agent was 12 turns into a task. The daemon crashed. What now?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Nothing is lost. Every turn boundary writes a drain snapshot to <code class="text-primary">.ostk/drain/&lt;lineage_id&gt;.json</code> — full message history, token accounting, model + tools + permissions config. When the daemon restarts, it acquires the anchor lock, marks stale sessions <code class="text-primary">Orphaned</code>, then <code class="text-primary">rehydrate_revivable_orphans</code> reads the drain snapshots and rebuilds each session from its last turn. The agent picks up at turn 13 with full context.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Drain snapshots at every turn boundary · lineage state machine (<code class="text-primary">Active → Orphaned → Reaped</code>) · revival policy (<code class="text-primary">revive</code> default, <code class="text-primary">reap</code>, or <code class="text-primary">ask</code>) · Anchor Exclusivity (invariant VIII) keeps two daemons from forking lineages.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/drain.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/anchor.rs</code> (<code>orphan_previous_lineages</code> + <code>rehydrate_revivable_orphans</code> + <code>reap_unmanaged_orphans</code>).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 02 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_02 // ISOLATE_BLAST_RADIUS</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">I want to spawn a fleet for one task without it seeing the rest of the project.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Sub-stacks isolate work by scope. <code class="text-primary">.ostk/stacks/&lt;name&gt;/</code> contains its own journal, its own drain directory, its own inbox, and its own nudges. Agents inside the sub-stack see only that scope; the parent anchor sees only the inbox/nudge channel. Token budgets, capability pins, and audit lineage all stay scoped. When the sub-stack seals, the journal collapses into the parent as a single attestation.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Scoped journal + scoped drain + inbox/nudge IPC channels · Root Namespace Isolation (invariant IV) · sub-stack state machine (<code class="text-primary">Spawning → Active → Sealed → Reaped</code>, or <code class="text-primary">Failed</code>).
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/sub_stack.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/sandbox.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 03 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_03 // CLIENT_DISCONNECTED</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">My TUI lost the socket. Is the agent still running?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Yes. Clients are transient by design — TUI, MCP bridges, CLI one-shots, IDE extensions all attach and detach without affecting the underlying session. The anchor holds session state in memory; clients are subscribers. Reattach over the kernel socket with <code class="text-primary">client/attach</code> and pick up the live event stream from where you left off. The anchor's lifecycle is decoupled from any client's.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Anchor as long-lived process · transient-client JSON-RPC protocol (<code class="text-primary">client/attach</code>, <code class="text-primary">client/detach</code>, <code class="text-primary">client/subscribe</code>) · Connection Continuity (invariant X) makes reattach lossless.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/serve/server.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/serve/client.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/anchor.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 04 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_04 // WORKER_HUNG_MID_FLIGHT</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">A worker stopped responding. Do I wait for a daemon restart?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      No — recovery happens in-process. Each session writes a heartbeat at every kernel-mediated step. The scheduler's tick loop watches the heartbeat table; when it expires past threshold, the worker is marked crashed, reaped, and hot-rehydrated from its last drain snapshot — all without restarting the daemon. The heartbeat is the timeout mechanism Bounded Wait (invariant I) requires; the rehydrate path is the same one crash recovery uses.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Heartbeat at every kernel call · scheduler tick loop · drain-snapshot rehydrate · Bounded Wait (I) gives the heartbeat its deadline · Subreaper (III) reaps the dead worker process.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/scheduler.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/heartbeat.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The composition -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">THE_COMPOSITION</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Four problems, one shape.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Every answer above composes the same four primitives: <strong class="text-on-surface">the anchor</strong> (long-lived daemon process holding the socket and the in-memory projection), <strong class="text-on-surface">the lineage</strong> (stable identity for ongoing work — <code class="text-primary">scheduler</code>, <code class="text-primary">worker-a</code> — outliving both client and anchor), <strong class="text-on-surface">the drain snapshot</strong> (reconstructable state at every turn boundary), and <strong class="text-on-surface">the sub-stack</strong> (isolation boundary for scoped work).
    </p>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-6">
      What stays true across all four: the anchor is a cache, not a ledger. The journal + drain snapshots on disk are the truth. <code class="text-primary">ostk daemon restart</code> swaps a rebuilt binary cleanly without losing audit lineage. Reset the anchor and the registries rebuild from journal replay; reset the registries and the kernel keeps writing.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 max-w-2xl">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-3">REVIVAL_POLICY</div>
      <pre class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="text-primary">LIMIT</span> revival_policy revive   <span class="text-outline"># auto-recover from drain snapshot (default)</span>
<span class="text-primary">LIMIT</span> revival_policy reap     <span class="text-outline"># drop on orphan — don't recover</span>
<span class="text-primary">LIMIT</span> revival_policy ask      <span class="text-outline"># leave orphaned, operator decides</span></pre>
      <p class="font-body text-[11px] text-outline">
        Set in the Agentfile per worker. Ask-pending lineages: <code class="text-primary">ostk lineage resolve &lt;id&gt; --revive</code> or <code class="text-primary">--reap</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="metadata-ribbon border-t border-surface-variant">
    <span class="font-label text-[10px] text-secondary mr-4">RELATED:</span>
    <a href="/docs/architecture/"><Icon name="architecture" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />ARCHITECTURE</a>
    <a href="/docs/kernel-spec/"><Icon name="memory" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />KERNEL_SPEC</a>
    <a href="/docs/agentfile/"><Icon name="smart_toy" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />AGENTFILE</a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
